{"cursor":"2359","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n was the brother-in-law of Toyotomi Hideyoshi and one of his chief advisors.\n Asano also fought for Hideyoshi in a number of campaigns during the Sengoku\n period of the 16th century of Japan.\n\nAsano accompanied Hideyoshi in his campaign against the MÅri clan, and fought in\nHideyoshi's invasions of Korea. He also fought for Hideyoshi against the HÅjÅ\nclan in 1590 and captured Iwatsuki and Edo castles.\n\nAsano was also appointed by Hideyoshi to a Commission of Five ([[Go-BugyÅ]])\nalong with Ishida Mitsunari, Maeda Gen'i, Mashita Nagamori and Natsuka Masaie.\nAsano held seniority over the Commissioners, who were charged with governing the\ncapital of Kyoto and the Home Provinces or [[Kansai|Kinai]]. A close advisor to\nHideyoshi, Asano devised the land survey and a number of other policies enacted\nunder his rule.\n\nIn 1598, Hideyoshi's invasions were coming to an end, and Asano was sent to\nKorea with his fellow Commissioner Ishida Mitsunari to arrange for Japanese\nwithdrawal. Asano was assured by the generals that the war was going well, and\nthat they were on the verge of victory. Ishida disagreed, however, and supported\nwithdrawal from Korea. Returning to Japan, daimyÅ (feudal lords) from across the\ncountry became involved in the debate, and the disagreement grew into a major\ngovernmental rift. The Go-BugyÅ disbanded soon afterwards, having already been\nreplaced by the Council of Five Elders (TairÅ) by Hideyoshi before his death.\n\nNagamasa was succeeded by his son Asano Yoshinaga.\n","linknr":111,"url":"Asano_Nagamasa","recorded":1364139962,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Asano_Nagamasa&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Asano_Nagamasa&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:Recent